[[File:Mount Takasu (Fukuoka), sanchou.jpg|thumb|220px|right|{{center|Summit of Mount Takasu}}]]
'''Mount Takasu''' (高祖山, Takasu-yama) is a mountain with an elevation of 416 meters located on the border of [[Fukuoka City]] and [[Itoshima City]] in [[Fukuoka Prefecture]], Japan. The mountain is home to the remains of the ancient {{ill|Ito Castle|ja|怡土城|12=draft}} and the medieval {{ill|Takasu Castle|ja|高祖城|12=draft}} (also known as Harada Castle).

== Name ==
The origin of the name "Mount Takasu" is unclear. Historical records refer to it as "Takasu," "Peak of Takasu," and "Mount Takasu." Given the presence of {{ill|Takasu Shrine|ja|高祖神社|12=draft}} at the western foot of the mountain, it is uncertain whether the shrine derived its name from the mountain or vice versa. The name "Takasu" appears to have been widely recognized in the region.<br />
The mountain is also locally known as "Sleeping Ox Mountain" (臥牛山, Gagyūzan) due to its resemblance to a reclining ox, particularly when viewed from {{ill|Shito Shrine|ja|志登神社|12=draft}}. This characteristic is visible from many parts of [[Itoshima City]].<br />
South of Mount Takasu lies another peak historically referred to as "Kushifuru Mountain," according to records that note, "It was mistakenly called Kushifuru Mountain due to its location behind a house."<ref>‘Itoshima Gunshi’ Fukuoka Prefecture Historical Collections (1927)</ref>.

== Ito Castle ==
{{main|Ito Castle}}
The western slopes of the mountain hosted {{ill|Ito Castle|ja|怡土城|12=draft}}, constructed by {{ill|Kibi no Makibi|ja|吉備真備|12=draft}} (later replaced by {{ill|Saeki no Imami|ja|佐伯今毛人|12=draft}}) over 12 years, from June of {{ill|Tenpyō Shōhō|ja|天平勝宝|12=draft}} 8 (756 CE) to February of {{ill|Jingō-keiun|ja|神護景雲|12=draft}} 2 (768 CE).

== Takasu Castle ==
{{main|Takasu Castle}}
While the exact date of Ito Castle's abandonment is unknown, its ruins were later repurposed. In {{ill|Kenchō|ja|建長|12=draft}} 1 (1249 CE), {{ill|Harada Tanetsugu|ja|原田種継|12=draft}} and his son {{ill|Harada Taneyori|ja|原田種頼|12=draft}} built {{ill|Takasu Castle|ja|高祖城|12=draft}} on this site. The summit features two structures: the upper castle (honmaru) and the lower castle (ninomaru). The slopes house {{ill|Takasu Shrine|ja|高祖神社|12=draft}}, revered by the Harada clan, and {{ill|Kinryūji Temple|ja|金龍寺 (福岡市)|12=draft}}, the family temple of the Harada.<ref>‘Kaisei Harada-ki’ by Kodama Takku (1817)</ref>.

== Hiking ==
Mount Takasu offers several hiking routes. The trail from the {{ill|Imajuku Outdoor Activity Center|ja|今宿野外活動センター|12=draft}} connects to nearby peaks, including Takochi Mountain and {{ill|Kanōdake|ja|叶岳|12=draft}}, allowing for a mini traversing experience. Other routes include paths from Takakuraji, Nyoi, and the rear of Takasu Shrine. The trails are well-maintained, and the summit can be reached within 1–2 hours. Although the summit itself is wooded and offers limited views, the ridge trails provide expansive vistas of [[Hakata Bay]], [[Fukuoka City]], and the surrounding mountains, such as {{ill|Mount Kaya|ja|可也山|12=draft}}, {{ill|Mount Uki|ja|浮嶽|12=draft}}, {{ill|Mount Hagan|ja|羽金山|12=draft}}, {{ill|Mount Rai|ja|雷山|12=draft}}, and the {{ill|Sefuri Mountains|ja|脊振山地|12=draft}}.

